Summary: This section explains how to improve performance by using simpler materials for distant Level of Detail (LOD) meshes.

Using simpler materials for distant LOD meshes can improve performance by reducing the per-pixel shading load on the GPU. While LOD meshes reduce vertex count, the material shading cost remains the same. Reducing this shading load by using less complex materials where visual difference is minimal can lead to performance gains.

It's important to measure performance gains carefully, as an increase in the number of unique materials can also incur a performance cost. However, simpler materials for distant LODs can still result in a net performance improvement due to fewer per-pixel calculations.

For materials on distant LOD meshes, consider disabling expensive features such as:
- Normal Map (especially on mobile platforms)
- Rim
- Clearcoat
- Anisotropy
- Height
- Subsurface Scattering
- Back Lighting
- Refraction
- Proximity Fade
---CHUNK---
