Path: godot/tutorials/3d/visibility_ranges.rst
Summary: This section explains how to use dithering for Level of Detail (LOD) transitions in Godot 3D rendering.

Use dithering for LOD transitions. Godot currently only supports alpha-based fading for visibility ranges, but dithering can be used by employing different materials for different LOD levels.

Advantages of dithering over alpha blending for LOD transitions:
* Higher performance, as dithering transparency is faster to render than alpha blending.
* Avoids visual glitches caused by transparency sorting issues during LOD transitions.

The disadvantage of dithering is that a "noisy" pattern is visible during LOD fade transitions. This may be less noticeable at higher viewport resolutions or with temporal antialiasing enabled.

Since distance fade in BaseMaterial3D only supports fading up close or fading when far away, this setup is best used with only two LODs.

Key Rules for setting up dithering for LOD transitions:
* Ensure **Begin Margin** and **End Margin** are set to 0.0 on both MeshInstance3D nodes, as hysteresis or alpha fade are not desired.
* On both MeshInstance3D nodes, decrease **Begin** by the desired fade transition distance and increase **End** by the same distance. This is required for the dithering transition to be visible.
* On the MeshInstance3D displayed up close, edit its material. Set its **Distance Fade** mode to **Object Dither**. Set **Min Distance** to the same value as the visibility range **End**. Set **Max Distance** to the same value minus the fade transition distance.
* On the MeshInstance3D displayed far away, edit its material. Set its **Distance Fade** mode to **Object Dither**. Set **Min Distance** to the same value as the visibility range **Begin**. Set **Max Distance** to the same value plus the fade transition distance.